title: N-14(d,n)O-15 and N-15(d,n)O-16 reactions.

x4freetext: Small plastic scintillators were used as proton
recoil counters to detect the neutrons. The detectors
were mounted on Dumont 6292 phototubes.
A gas target was made of 10-mil-wall stainless steel
tubing with a gold beam stop and a 0.01-mil nickel
entrance window. The target thickness was 20 keV or
less.
The incident deuteron energy was corrected for the
energy loss in traversing the nickel foil and
one-half the target gas. The corrections to the cross
section for background amounted to a maximum of 15%.
Corrections were also made for the loss of recoil
protons from the sides and ends of the counter.
Absolute error. The major source of
error in the cross sections are:
(1) errors in reading the target pressure,
(2) errors in the conversion from a pulse height to
energy scale,
(3) approximations in calculating the detector
solid angles, and
(4) approximations in the calculation of side and end
effect corrections.
Data digitizing error
Error bars show typical errors due to
counting statistics only.

x4freetext: No explanation of relative units is given.
Right detector is a cylinder 5.49 mm long by 6.36 mm in
diameter.  For the angular distributions at 1.806,
2.103, and 2.999 MeV two such cylinders mounted in a
copper block were used.
The angular resolution ranged from +-2 degr. at angle
equal 0 degr., to +-11 degr. at angle equal 90 degr.
